[{"location":"functions/#Functions","page":"Functions","title":"Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/#Application-to-summer-precipitation-recorded-in-Montréal,-QC","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application to summer precipitation recorded in Montréal, QC","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"In this section, we show that the EGP model based on the truncated Beta distribution can be used to model non-zero precipitation, which corresponds to exceedances above the very low threshold of 0, while maintaining the tail behavior.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"using Extremes, ExtendedExtremes, DataFrames, Dates, CSV, Distributions, Gadfly","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/#Data","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Data","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"The daily summer precipitation (May–October) recorded at the Montréal-Trudeau International Airport meteorological station (Québec, Canada) from 2000 to 2020 are investigated. This dataset can be loaded using the ExtendedExtremes.dataset provided for this tutorial.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"data = ExtendedExtremes.dataset(\"pcp\")\nfilter!(row -> row.Date>= Date(2000,1,1), data)\nfilter!(row -> month(row.Date) in 5:10, data)\ndropmissing!(data)\nfirst(data,5)","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/#Modeling-the-non-zero-precipitation","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Modeling the non-zero precipitation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"The EGP parameter estimation with maximum likelihood is performed with the fit_mle function.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"u = 0.0\ny = data.pcp[data.pcp .> u] .- u;\n\nfd = fit_mle(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto{TBeta}, y)","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"Several diagnostic plots for assessing the accuracy of the EGP model fitted to the Montréal data are can be shown with the diagnosticplots function:","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"set_default_plot_size(16cm, 16cm)\nExtendedExtremes.diagnosticplots(y, fd)","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/precipitation/","page":"Application: Precipitation","title":"Application: Precipitation","text":"The diagnostic plots consist in the probability plot (upper left panel), the quantile plot (upper right panel), the density plot (lower left panel) and the return level plot (lower right panel). These plots can be displayed separately using respectively the probplot, qqplot, histplot and returnlevelplot functions.","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/#Contributing","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"Contributions are welcomed. Here's the workflow for development of new features, refactoring and bugfix.","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"master             # Stable branch, always ready to be tagged\ndev                # Development branch. New features, refactoring, bug and hotfix\n                   # are integrated into dev before going into master.\nfeature/           # New feature needs a `feature` prefix\n   <feature-name>     \nrefactor/          # Refactoring are tagged with a `refactor` prefix\n   <refactor-name>\nbug/               # Prefix for bugs found during development\n   <bug-fix>       \nhotfix/            # Prefix for hotfix (bugs for deployed versions)\n   <hot-fix>    ","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/#Tutorial","page":"Getting started","title":"Tutorial","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"This tutorial shows the functionalities of ExtendedExtremes.jl. They are illustrated by reproducing some of the results shown by Gamet & Jalbert (2022).","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"Before executing this tutorial, make sure to have installed the following packages:","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"ExtendedExtremes.jl \nExtremes.jl\nCSV.jl\nDataFrames.jl \nDates.jl\nDistributions.jl \nGadfly.jl ","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"and import them using the following command:","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/","page":"Getting started","title":"Getting started","text":"using ExtendedExtremes, Extremes, CSV, DataFrames, Dates, Distributions, Gadfly","category":"page"},{"location":"#ExtendedExtremes-Package","page":"ExtendedExtremes Package","title":"ExtendedExtremes Package","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"ExtendedExtremes Package","title":"ExtendedExtremes Package","text":"ExtendedExtremes.jl provides a collection of extended Generalized Pareto distributions (EGPD) and related functions. In particular, the extended generalized Pareto distributions described in Gamet & Jalbert (2022) and related methods are implemented, such as:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"ExtendedExtremes Package","title":"ExtendedExtremes Package","text":"Sampling from distributions\nProbability density functions (pdf) and their logarithm (logpdf)\nCumulative distribution functions (cdf) and their logarithm (logcdf)\nMaximum likelihood estimation\nDiagnostic plots for assessing model accuracy","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"ExtendedExtremes Package","title":"ExtendedExtremes Package","text":"note: Note\nThe ExtendedExtremes.jl library is currently being refactored. The \tsupport for extended generalized Pareto families proposed in Naveau et al. \t(2016) has been abandoned as well as some other functionalities. However, it \tis still possible to find these abandoned features in ExtendedExtremes.jl \tv0.1.1.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Reference","page":"ExtendedExtremes Package","title":"Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"ExtendedExtremes Package","title":"ExtendedExtremes Package","text":"Gamet, P. & Jalbert, J. (2022). A flexible extended generalized Pareto distribution for tail estimation. Environmetrics, 33(6), e2744.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/#Extended-generalized-Pareto-(EGP)-distributions","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended generalized Pareto (EGP) distributions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"The extended generalized Pareto families proposed in Gamet & Jalbert (2022) are implemented and ready to be used just like any UnivariateDistribution from the Distributions.jl package.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"Any distribution function F_V on the unit interval that satisfies the conditions in Gamet & Jalbert (2022) can be used to extend the GeneralizedPareto distribution object using the ExtendedGeneralizedPareto constructor.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"To extend the GP model, the following distributions can be used:","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"Power\nTNormal\nTBeta","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/#EGP-model-based-on-the-power-function","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"EGP model based on the power function","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"The ExtendedGeneralizedPareto method is first illustrated using the Power function extension as proposed by Papastathopoulos & Tawn (2013).","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"using ExtendedExtremes, Distributions, Gadfly","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"l1 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(Power(0.8), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 0.8\"], linestyle=[:dash])\nl2 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(Power(1.0), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 1.0\"])\nl3 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(Power(1.5), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 1.5\"], linestyle=[:dot])\n\nxticks = [0.00, 0.50, 1.00, 1.50, 2.00]\nyticks = [0.00, 0.50, 1.00, 1.50, 2.00]\n\nset_default_plot_size(13cm, 9cm)\nplot(l1, l2, l3,\n    Guide.colorkey(title=\"\", labels=[\"κ = 0.8\",\"κ = 1.0\", \"κ = 1.5\"]),\n    Guide.xticks(ticks=xticks), Guide.yticks(ticks=yticks),\n    Guide.ylabel(\"\"), Guide.xlabel(\"\"), Guide.title(\"EGP-Power\")\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/#EGP-model-based-on-the-truncated-normal-distribution","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"EGP model based on the truncated normal distribution","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"Gamet & Jalbert (2022) proposed an EGP model based on the TNormal distribution.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"using ExtendedExtremes, Distributions, Gadfly","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"l1 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(TNormal(.00001), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 0\"], linestyle=[:dash])\nl2 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(TNormal(1), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 1\"])\nl3 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(TNormal(5), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 5\"], linestyle=[:dot])\n\nxticks = [0.00, 0.50, 1.00, 1.50, 2.00]\nyticks = [0.20, 0.40, 0.60, 0.80, 1.00]\n\nset_default_plot_size(13cm, 9cm)\nplot(l1, l2, l3,\n    Guide.colorkey(title=\"\", labels=[\"κ = 0\",\"κ = 1\", \"κ = 5\"]),\n    Guide.xticks(ticks=xticks), Guide.yticks(ticks=yticks),\n    Guide.ylabel(\"\"), Guide.xlabel(\"\"), Guide.title(\"EGP-TNormal\")\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/#EGP-model-based-on-the-truncated-Beta-distribution","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"EGP model based on the truncated Beta distribution","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"Gamet & Jalbert (2022) also proposed an EGP model based on the TBeta distribution.","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"using ExtendedExtremes, Distributions, Gadfly","category":"page"},{"location":"tutorial/distributions/","page":"Extended GP distributions","title":"Extended GP distributions","text":"l1 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(TBeta(0.8), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 0.8\"], linestyle=[:dash])\nl2 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(TBeta(1.0), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 1.0\"])\nl3 = layer(x -> pdf(ExtendedGeneralizedPareto(TBeta(1.5), GeneralizedPareto(1,0)), x), 0 , 2, color=[\"κ = 1.5\"], linestyle=[:dot])\n\nxticks = [0.00, 0.50, 1.00, 1.50, 2.00]\nyticks = [0.25, 0.50, 0.75, 1.00, 1.25]\n\nset_default_plot_size(13cm, 9cm)\nplot(l1, l2, l3,\n    Guide.colorkey(title=\"\", labels=[\"κ = 0.8\",\"κ = 1.0\", \"κ = 1.5\"]),\n    Guide.xticks(ticks=xticks), Guide.yticks(ticks=yticks),\n    Guide.ylabel(\"\"), Guide.xlabel(\"\"), Guide.title(\"EGP-TBeta\")\n)","category":"page"}]
